%\section{Real part of Gamma coefficient: Four-wave-mixing measurements}
\section{Four-wave-mixing: Re\{$ \gamma $\}}
We couple into the waveguide two cw beams, an amplified pump and a signal, which generates an idler signal. We measure the conversion efficiency as a function of the wavelength separation between pump and signal (Fig.~\ref{fig:fwmBw}). Assuming that at these power levels TPA is negligible, we fit the results to the equation shown in Ref.~\cite{Vallaitis2009} for the FWM efficiency $ \eta $ formula:

%(Fig.~\ref{fig:fwmSetup}

\begin{equation}
	\eta ^2=\frac{\alpha_0^2}{\alpha_0^2+\Delta \beta^2}\left[ 1+ 4e^{-\alpha_0L}\frac{sin^2(L\Delta\beta/2)}{(1-e^{-\alpha_0L})^2} \right] \nonumber	
\end{equation}

where $ \Delta\beta $ for a detuning $ \Delta\lambda = \lambda_p-\lambda_s$ is given by:

\begin{equation}
	\Delta \beta=\frac{2\pi cD_2}{\lambda_p^2}\Delta\lambda^2 \nonumber
\end{equation}


